{"guid": "BEIS_002", "title": "Employment tribunal claims", "measure_summary": "This data measures employment tribunal claims made by people who feel they have suffered a workplace grievance.\r\n\r\nTypical reasons for an employee to make a claim are:\r\n\r\n* gender, age or race discrimination\r\n\r\n* unfair dismissal (when a person loses their job through unfair compulsory or voluntary redundancy practices, or through constructive dismissal, when they have been \u2018forced out\u2019 of a job)\r\n\r\n* breach of contract (when the terms and conditions of a person\u2019s employment \u2013 sick pay, holiday pay, hours worked \u2013 have been unfairly changed)\r\n\r\n* unauthorised deduction of earnings (when an employee has not been paid the agreed sum of money for work done)\r\n\r\nThe figures are based on surveys from 2 years: 2007 and 2012. This is the most recent data available for employment tribunal claims. \r\n\r\nThe data for 2007 includes \u2018multiple claims\u2019 \u2013 cases where a group of people have the same grievance against an employer and the case is settled collectively.\r\n\r\nHowever the data for 2012 only measures \u2018single claims\u2019 \u2013 claims by a single individual.", "summary": "* in 2007, 14% of employment tribunal claims (including group claims) were made by people from ethnic minorities, though ethnic minority employees made up only 9% of the total working population\r\n\r\n* in 2012, the percentage of claims (excluding group claims) made by people from ethnic minorities was 18%, which was also higher than the percentage of ethnic minority employees in the total working population that year (10%)\r\n\r\n* these figures indicate that ethnic minority employees were more likely than White employees to make an employment tribunal claim\r\n\r\n* where the employment tribunal related to discrimination, ethnic minorities made up nearly a quarter of claims in both 2007 and 2012", "geographic_coverage": "England, Wales and Scotland", "lowest_level_of_geography": "National", "time_covered": "2007 and 2012", "need_to_know": "The data is based on a Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) survey of around 2,000 respondents. \r\n\r\nIn 2007, the data was analysed by claim, rather than by the person making the claim. While 90% of these cases related to single claims made by individual people, some cases may have been part of multiple claims made by groups.\r\n\r\nIn 2012, multiple claims were excluded from the data. Therefore, results from 2007 should not be compared with results from 2012.", "ethnicity_definition_summary": "For this data, the number of respondents to the survey was too small to draw any firm conclusions about differences between ethnic groups. Therefore, the data is broken down into the following 5 broad categories: \r\n\r\n* White \r\n* Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups \r\n* Asian/Asian British\r\n* Black/African/Caribbean/Black British \r\n* Other ethnic group", "ethnicity_definition_detail": "", "source_text": "Survey of Employment Tribunals Applications (SETA)", "source_url": "https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/survey-of-employment-tribunal-applications-2013", "department_source": "Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy", "published_date": "1 February 2010", "last_update_date": "1 June 2014", "next_update_date": "Autumn 2018", "frequency": "Every 4 to 5 years", "related_publications": "[Sixth Periodic Survey of Employment Tribunal Applications 2013](https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/382134/bis-14-1242-technical-report-sixth-periodic-survey-of-employment-tribunal-applications-2013.pdf)", "contact_name": "Ivan Bishop", "contact_phone": "0207 215 1831", "contact_email": "lm.correspondence@beis.gov.uk", "data_source_purpose": "The Survey of Employment Tribunal Applications (SETA) aims to provide information on the characteristics of claimants in, and the key features of, employment tribunals.", "methodology": "The Survey of Employment Tribunal Applications (SETA) 2008 was a survey using a simple random sample taken from all employment tribunal cases which had closed between January 2007 and January 2008. SETA 2008 achieved 2,020 computer-assisted telephone interviews with claimants, a response rate of 66%.\r\n\r\nSETA 2013 took a random sample from of all single employment tribunal claims which had closed between January 2012 and December 2012. The sample was stratified on case outcome (successful at tribunal, unsuccessful at tribunal, Acas settled, other settled, withdrawn, dismissed) and case track (fast, standard and open). SETA 2013 achieved 1,988 telephone interviews (CATI) with claimants were achieved, as response rate of 53%.", "data_type": "Survey", "suppression_rules": "Percentages lower than 2% are suppressed", "disclosure_control": "Data security was assured through the data being strored and processed through systems meeting the information management security standard ISO 27001. The research organisation carrying out the survey was fully compliant with the Code of Conduct of the Market Research Society, and compliant with the Data Protection Act 1998.", "estimation": "Percentages are rounded to the nearest whole number", "type_of_statistic": "", "qmi_url": "", "further_technical_information": "", "dimensions": [{"guid": "e79e55a9167f046d564cd33e32e12afe67e77831", "title": "Employment tribunal claims by ethnicity", "measure": "BEIS_002", "time_period": "2007 and 2012", "summary": "This data shows that:\r\n\r\n* In 2012, White people made 82% of all employment tribunal claims (excluding group claims), but a higher proportion (85%) of those claims which were for unfair dismissal, under the Wages Act or \u2018Other\u2019 grievances \r\n\r\n* Black people made up 2% of the total working population in 2012, but 7% of the claims (excluding group claims) for unfair dismissal, 8% for breach of contract, 6% for unauthorised deduction of earnings, 12% for discrimination and 4% for \u2018Other\u2019 grievances", "chart": {"type": "bar", "title": {"text": "Total employment tribunal claims by ethnicity"}, "xAxis": {"title": {"text": ""}, "categories": ["Asian", "Black", "Mixed", "White", "Other", "Unknown"]}, "yAxis": {"title": {"text": ""}}, "series": [{"name": "2007", "data": [{"y": 5, "category": "Asian", "text": "number"}, {"y": 5, "category": "Black", "text": "number"}, {"y": 2, "category": "Mixed", "text": "number"}, {"y": 86, "category": "White", "text": "number"}, {"y": 2, "category": "Other", "text": "number"}, {"y": 0, "category": "Unknown", "text": "?"}], "name_value": 2007}, {"name": "2012", "data": [{"y": 5, "category": "Asian", "text": "number"}, {"y": 7, "category": "Black", "text": "number"}, {"y": 2, "category": "Mixed", "text": "number"}, {"y": 82, "category": "White", "text": "number"}, {"y": 0, "category": "Other", "text": "?"}, {"y": 2, "category": "Unknown", "text": "number"}], "name_value": 2012}], "number_format": {"multiplier": 1, "prefix": "", "suffix": "%", "min": 0, "max": 100}, "version": "1.1", "chart": {"type": "bar"}}, "table": {"group_columns": ["", "All", "Unfair dismissal", "Breach of contract", "Wages Act", "Discrimination", "Other (including redundancy payments)"], "type": "grouped", "category": "Standard Ethnicity", "group_column": "employment tribunal jurisdiction", "columns": ["2007", "2012"], "data": [{"category": "Asian", "relationships": {"is_parent": false, "is_child": false, "parent": "Asian"}, "order": 100, "values": ["5", "5", "3", "5", "4", "5", "5", "3", "11", "9", "3", "3"], "sort_values": [5, 5, 3, 5, 4, 5, 5, 3, 11, 9, 3, 3]}, {"category": "Black", "relationships": {"is_parent": false, "is_child": false, "parent": "Black"}, "order": 200, "values": ["5", "7", "4", "7", "4", "8", "5", "6", "8", "12", "3", "4"], "sort_values": [5, 7, 4, 7, 4, 8, 5, 6, 8, 12, 3, 4]}, {"category": "Mixed", "relationships": {"is_parent": false, "is_child": false, "parent": "Mixed"}, "order": 300,